    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "A matrix acts on a vector and rotates it. Every arrow in the plane points somewhere new. Almost every arrow.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reveal"
      },
      "card": {
        "dek": "Eigenvectors: the directions a matrix can't turn",
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.4,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-eigen-directions/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "t_start": 8,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Apply a linear map to a fan of arrows and watch them scatter to new angles. But two directions come out pointing exactly where they went in. Why does every matrix have these special directions?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reveal"
      },
      "card": {
        "dek": "Every matrix rotates most arrows \u2014 but some it can only stretch. Why must those directions exist?",
        "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.42,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-eigen-directions/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 18,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Take an arbitrary matrix. Apply it to a ring of unit arrows. Watch where they land \u2014 they fan out to new directions, rotated and scaled by different amounts.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transform"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.64,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-eigen-directions/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 29,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Most arrows tilt after the transformation. The question is whether any arrow stays on its own line \u2014 stretched but not rotated. That arrow would satisfy A times v equals lambda times v.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transform"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.54,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-eigen-directions/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 39,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "The eigenvectors are exactly those arrows. Watch the transformation: a general arrow fans to a new angle, but the eigenvectors slide only along their own line.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transform"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.85,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-eigen-directions/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 51,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Each eigenvector has a corresponding eigenvalue \u2014 the stretch factor. A negative eigenvalue means the arrow flips and stretches. It still stays on its own line.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scale"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.03,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-eigen-directions/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 62,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "In quantum mechanics, measuring an observable projects the system into an eigenstate. The eigenvalue is the measurement outcome \u2014 the number you read off the detector.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.56,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-eigen-directions/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-eigen-directions/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION",
      "t_start": 73,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Energy levels, quantum numbers, spin outcomes \u2014 all of quantum mechanics is built on finding the invariant directions of the right operator.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
